  "slug": "crown-of-turkey",
  "title": "Crown of Turkey",
  "subtitle": "Just the breast joint, roasted in under two hours with a sage butter and a bacon blanket",
  "excerpt": "A turkey crown is the breast section with the legs removed, sold on or off the bone. It roasts in half the time of a whole bird, with none of the timing anxiety of juggling breast and leg. Eight people are served from a 2.5 kg crown without waste.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Delia Smith, Delia's Happy Christmas (2009): turkey crown roasting guide. Nigella Lawson, Feast (2004): sage and bacon-covered crown. British supermarket-driven popularisation from the 1990s onwards.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "turkey crown",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr38q30000fcv4rz69t36p"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " eliminates the chief problem of whole-bird roasting: the legs needing far more cooking than the breast. With the legs gone, the roasting time shortens to around 1 hour 45 minutes for a 2.5 kg crown, and the internal temperature at which you pull it is a consistent 70-72°C throughout.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sage butter under the skin seasons the flesh and keeps it moist during the long dry heat. Streaky bacon laid in overlapping strips over the breast is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "barding",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr38qu0001fcv447syf1qn"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ": it self-bastes the crown as it renders, and the rashers themselves are a cook's perk when they come off crispily at the end.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
