      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Butter the crown and bard",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 190°C (170°C fan). Beat the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{unsalted-butter}} of butter",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with the chopped ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sage}} of sage",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", lemon juice if using, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Ease the skin away from the breast and push two thirds of the butter mixture under the skin, spreading it across both lobes. Rub the remaining butter over the outside of the skin. Lay the bacon rashers in overlapping strips across the top of the crown.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Roast and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Set the crown in the roasting pan and roast for 1 hour 30 minutes. Remove the bacon rashers and return the crown to the oven for a final 15 minutes to colour the skin. The crown is done when a probe at the thickest part of the breast reads 70-72°C. Transfer to a warm board and rest for 20 minutes; the temperature will carry over by another 3-4°C during resting.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the gravy",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pour off excess fat from the pan. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{white-wine-dry}} of white wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " if using and scrape the fond over medium heat. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and simmer for 5 minutes. Season and strain into a warm jug. Carve the crown at the table in long, even slices across the grain.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Remove the bacon earlier, at the 1 hour 15 minute mark. Check oven temperature with a thermometer.",
              "cause": "Bacon was left on too long, or oven temperature was lower than expected",
              "symptom": "Skin is pale after 1 hour 45 minutes"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Probe at 1 hour and adjust. There is no minimum time, only a temperature to reach. Pull it when the probe is right.",
              "cause": "Crown was closer to 3 kg and cooked faster than 2.5 kg",
              "symptom": "Meat reads 70°C at 1 hour but you expected longer"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Pull at 70-72°C and rest promptly. Serve with plenty of gravy and stuffing to compensate.",
              "cause": "Overcooked past 75°C, or the crown sat unrested for too long",
              "symptom": "Meat is dry and stringy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Two thirds under the skin, one third on the outside is the right ratio. A small amount of fond in the pan is fine; charred solid residue means the heat was too high.",
              "cause": "Too much butter was pushed under the skin, or the crown was on too high a heat",
              "symptom": "Butter under the skin has leaked into the pan and burned"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The turkey crown became Britain's default Christmas centrepiece for smaller households once supermarkets began selling them widely in the 1990s. It suits the household that wants the full roast experience without the size, the timing complexity, or the days of leftover turkey that follow a whole 7 kg bird. Eight people are fed comfortably, and the leftovers are manageable.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
